    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.10.39" />
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">JOHN GALEN HOWARD
                        <lb/>
                    ARCHITECT
                        <lb/>
                    FIRST NATIONAL BANK BUILDING
                        <lb/>
                    SAN FRANCISCO</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">39</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>December 10, 1923.</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt, Esq.,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson, Missouri.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>My dear John:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Many, many thanks for your kind letter of September 30 extending your sympathy for our sufferings in the Berkeley fire. Our losses were considerable but were mostly confined to th<del/><add>ings</add> that didn't mean very much to us and we were fairly well insured, so that after all<add>,</add> now that we can size up the situation<add>,</add> we find we are among the most fortunate of all those who were burnt out. We have taken a little house in San Francisco and are enjoying the adventure heartily, especially as we have our two oldest sons near at hand. Henry is living with us and Robert has a studio a few blocks away and usually drops in to dinner. Janette is a freshman in college and is living at her sorority but we see her week-ends, so you see we are pretty fortunate.</p>
                
                <p>Mrs. Howard and I are leaving tomorrow for a month's trip east -- New Orleans, Washington, New York, Boston and roundabout. Even when you have lost little that counts<add>,</add> the psychology of the fire is rotten. Mrs. Howard was ill at the time and for a couple of weeks after and is still not quite herself and I am as crabb<del/><add>ed</add> as they make them, so we are going to see what perfect freedom from anxiety and responsibility will do for us.</p>
                
                <p>It has been a great disappointment to me not to be able to arrange a date for you in San Francisco or Berkeley. Possibly Mr. Long has succeeded in doing so but I have not learned whether or not you are to be in these parts this winter. If so, I hope it will be after our return. We expect to be on the job again on or about January 14. It would be fine if we could run across you somewhere on your trip as I understand from Sterling you are already afield. If you happen to get this letter in time to communicate with me, while we are away, address me at the Century Club, 7 West 43d Street, New York City.</p>
                
                <p>With kind remembrances to all your family and with warmest personal affection,</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Faithfully yours</salute>
                
                    <note type="authorial">How comes along the poem?</note>
                
                    <signed>JG Howard</signed>
                
                    <note>JGH:VF</note>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
